            "method": 0.0,
            "other": 0.0,
            "title": 0.0
        }
    },
    {
        "text": "8 tablespoons light spelt flour, plus a little extra",
        "topic": {
            "blurb": 0.0,
            "ingredient": 1.0,
            "method": 0.0,
            "other": 0.0,
            "title": 0.0
        }
    },
    {
        "text": "a small bunch of spring herbs",
        "topic": {
            "blurb": 0.0,
            "ingredient": 1.0,
            "method": 0.0,
            "other": 0.0,
            "title": 0.0
        }
    },
    {
        "text": "150ml good olive oil",
        "topic": {
            "blurb": 0.0,
            "ingredient": 1.0,
            "method": 0.0,
            "other": 0.0,
            "title": 0.0
        }
    },
    {
        "text": "400g freshly podded peas",
        "topic": {
            "blurb": 0.0,
            "ingredient": 1.0,
            "method": 0.0,
            "other": 0.0,
            "title": 0.0
        }
    },
    {
        "text": "These are light, bright dumplings that are quick and easy to put together. It is a plate which is all about late spring: white, green and fresh. | use freshly podded peas here and | don\u2019t cook them: | love their pop and sweetness when they've not been cooked and they work against the softness of the ricotta. If podding peas sounds a bit much or fresh peas are hard to.get hold of for you, some briefly boiled frozen ones will work well too.",
        "topic": {
            "blurb": 1.0,
            "ingredient": 0.0,
            "method": 0.0,
            "other": 0.0,
            "title": 0.0
        }
    },
    {
        "text": "Chop your pistachios finely; you can do this in a food processor but be sure that you don\u2019t blitz them to a powder, as you still want them to have enough texture as if they had been finely chopped by hand.",
        "topic": {
            "blurb": 0.0,
            "ingredient": 0.0,
            "method": 1.0,
            "other": 0.0,
            "title": 0.0
        }
    },
    {
        "text": "Put the ricotta into a bowl with the pistachios, lemon zest, chopped chilli and the flour. Season well with salt and pepper and mix gently until it comes together as a dough.",
        "topic": {
            "blurb": 0.0,
            "ingredient": 0.0,
            "method": 1.0,
            "other": 0.0,
            "title": 0.0
        }
    },
    {
        "text": "Half fill a large saucepan with water and place it over a high heat.  Roll the ricotta mixture into about 20 little conker-sized balls. Very lightly dust in a little more flour and place on a chopping board while you wait for the water to boil.",
        "topic": {
            "blurb": 0.0,
            "ingredient": 0.0,
            "method": 1.0,
            "other": 0.0,
            "title": 0.0
        }
    },
    {
        "text": "Next, finely chop the herbs, put them into a bowl with the olive oil and the peas, and season with salt and pepper.",
        "topic": {
            "blurb": 0.0,
            "ingredient": 0.0,
            "method": 1.0,
            "other": 0.0,
            "title": 0.0
        }
    },
    {
        "text": "Once the water in the saucepan is at a boil, lower the dumplings in and cook them for 4-5 minutes, until they all rise and bob to the top.  Drain on kitchen paper and serve about 5 per person, topped with the herby peas and olive oil, ",
        "topic": {
            "blurb": 0.0,
            "ingredient": 0.0,
            "method": 1.0,
            "other": 0.0,
            "title": 0.0
        }
    },
